<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between oaked and unoaked Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oaked Chardonnays undergo fermentation or aging in oak barrels, developing rich flavors of vanilla, butter, and toast, with a creamy mouthfeel from malolactic fermentation. Unoaked versions are fermented in stainless steel, preserving the grape's natural acidity and showcasing pure fruit flavors like green apple, citrus, and mineral notes. The best choice depends on your preference for richness versus freshness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Chardonnay regions offer the best value for money?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Washington State, particularly Columbia Valley, produces exceptional Chardonnays at $15-25 that rival $40+ Burgundies, offering bright acidity and mineral complexity. Chile's Casablanca Valley delivers outstanding cool-climate Chardonnays under $20, while Australia's Adelaide Hills provides elegant, food-friendly options. For premium value, look to Oregon's Willamette Valley where top producers offer Burgundian-style wines at half the price of their French counterparts.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve the best Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Chardonnay at 45-50°F (7-10°C) for optimal flavor expression—cooler than room temperature but warmer than typical white wine service. Over-chilling mutes the wine's complexity and aromatics, while serving too warm makes oaked styles seem flabby and unoaked versions lose their refreshing character. Remove from refrigerator 10-15 minutes before serving, or use an ice bucket for 20 minutes to achieve the perfect temperature.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I identify a high-quality Chardonnay by the label?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for specific vineyard designations rather than generic regional labels, as single-vineyard Chardonnays typically represent higher quality fruit and winemaking. Terms like "sur lie aging" or "barrel fermented" indicate traditional techniques that add complexity. Avoid bottles with terms like "vanilla flavoring added" or generic descriptors like "smooth and buttery"—quality Chardonnays let their terroir and craftsmanship speak through authentic flavor development.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can premium Chardonnay age, and for how long?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Top-tier Chardonnays from Burgundy, California's Russian River Valley, and cool-climate regions can age 5-15 years, developing complex notes of honey, nuts, and dried fruits while maintaining their acidity. White Burgundies from producers like Louis Jadot or Domaine Leflaive peak around 7-10 years, while premium California Chardonnays typically show best at 3-8 years. Store bottles on their side in a cool, dark place at 55°F with consistent humidity to preserve their aging potential.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming all Chardonnays taste the same—the grape expresses terroir dramatically differently from Chablis's mineral crispness to Napa's rich oakiness. Many buyers also overlook vintage variation, especially in Burgundy where weather significantly impacts quality and price. Another error is judging quality solely by price; some $20 bottles from emerging regions outperform $60 legacy brands that rely on reputation rather than current quality.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Chardonnay good for wine beginners, and which styles should they try first?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Chardonnay is excellent for beginners because it offers a wide spectrum of styles to explore different wine preferences. Start with unoaked versions from Washington State or Chile to understand the grape's pure fruit character, then progress to lightly oaked California or Australian examples. This progression helps newcomers distinguish between grape characteristics and winemaking influences, building a foundation for appreciating more complex wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What alternatives should I try if I love high-quality Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">If you enjoy rich, oaked Chardonnays, explore white Rhône blends with Roussanne and Marsanne, or aged white Rioja made from Viura grapes, which offer similar texture and complexity. For fans of crisp, mineral Chardonnay like Chablis, try Austrian Grüner Veltliner or Loire Valley Muscadet, which share that bright acidity and stone-fruit character. Burgundy lovers should also explore Chardonnay's genetic parent, Pinot Blanc from Alsace.</p>
